Assignment 1 – Study Linux Commands
1. ls – most frequently used command in linux to list directories
2. pwd – print working directory command in linux
3. cd – navigation through the directories
4. mkdir – command used to create new directory in linux
5. mv – move or rename a file
6. cp – copying files.
7. rm – Delete file or directory
8. cat – display file contents on terminal
9. clear – clears the terminal screen
10. echo – prints text following this command
11. less – command that displays paged outputs in the terminal
12. man – displays manual all pages of linux commands
13. uname - gets basic info about OS
14. whoami – gets the active username
15. tar – command to extract and compress files
16. grep – search for string within output
17. head – return specified number of lines from top
18. tail – return specified number f lines from bottom.
19. diff – find different between two lines.
20. cmp – allows to check if two files are identical
21. comm – combined functionality of cmp and diff
22. sort – to sort content in a file while outputting.
23. export – export environment variables in linux
24. zip – zip files in linux
25. unzip – unzip files in linux
26. service – start and stop services
27. ps – isplay all active processes
28. kill – kills all active processes
29. df – display disk filesystem informaion
30.mount – mount file systems in linux
31. chmod – change file permissions
32.chown –granting ownership to files or folders
33.ifconfig – display network interfaces and IP addresses
34. traceroute – trace all network hops ro reach destination
35. wget – direct download files from internet
36. ufw – firewall command
37. iptables – base firewall for all other firewalls utilities to interface with
38. apt – package managers depending on distro
39. sudo – command to escalate privileges in linux
40. cal – view a command-line calendar
41. alias – create your own shortcuts for regularly used commands
42. dd - used for creating bootable usb sticks
43. whereis – locate binary source and manual pages for a command
44. whatis – find what a command is used for
45. top - view active processes that live with their system usage
46. useradd and usermod – to add and modify users data
47. w -- - to check how many users logged into linux
48. date – to check current time in linux
49. ls -a – list hidden files in directory
50. rm -rf – remove directory with files
